77static int *queuedConnectionTypes(const QMetaMethod &method)
78{
79 const auto parameterCount = method.parameterCount();
80 int *typeIds = new int[parameterCount + 1];
81 Q_CHECK_PTR(typeIds);
82 for (int i = 0; i < parameterCount; ++i) {
83 const QMetaType metaType = method.parameterMetaType(index: i);
84 if (metaType.flags() & QMetaType::IsPointer)
85 typeIds[i] = QMetaType::VoidStar;
86 else
87 typeIds[i] = metaType.id();
88 if (!typeIds[i] && method.parameterTypeName(index: i).endsWith(c: '*'))
89 typeIds[i] = QMetaType::VoidStar;
90 if (!typeIds[i]) {
91 const QByteArray typeName = method.parameterTypeName(index: i);
92 qCWarning(lcConnect,
93 "QObject::connect: Cannot queue arguments of type '%s'\n"
94 "(Make sure '%s' is registered using qRegisterMetaType().)",
95 typeName.constData(), typeName.constData());
96 delete[] typeIds;
97 return nullptr;
98 }
99 }
100 typeIds[parameterCount] = 0;
101
102 return typeIds;
103}
104
105static int *queuedConnectionTypes(const QArgumentType *argumentTypes, int argc)
106{
107 auto types = std::make_unique<int[]>(num: argc + 1);
108 for (int i = 0; i < argc; ++i) {
109 const QArgumentType &type = argumentTypes[i];
110 if (type.type())
111 types[i] = type.type();
112 else if (type.name().endsWith(c: '*'))
113 types[i] = QMetaType::VoidStar;
114 else
115 types[i] = QMetaType::fromName(name: type.name()).id();
116
117 if (!types[i]) {
118 qCWarning(lcConnect,
119 "QObject::connect: Cannot queue arguments of type '%s'\n"
120 "(Make sure '%s' is registered using qRegisterMetaType().)",
121 type.name().constData(), type.name().constData());
122 return nullptr;
123 }
124 }
125 types[argc] = 0;
126
127 return types.release();
128}

160QObjectPrivate::QObjectPrivate(int version)
161 : threadData(nullptr), currentChildBeingDeleted(nullptr)
162{
163 checkForIncompatibleLibraryVersion(version);
164
165 // QObjectData initialization
166 q_ptr = nullptr;
167 parent = nullptr; // no parent yet. It is set by setParent()
168 isWidget = false; // assume not a widget object
169 blockSig = false; // not blocking signals
170 wasDeleted = false; // double-delete catcher
171 isDeletingChildren = false; // set by deleteChildren()
172 sendChildEvents = true; // if we should send ChildAdded and ChildRemoved events to parent
173 receiveChildEvents = true;
174 postedEvents = 0;
175 extraData = nullptr;
176 metaObject = nullptr;
177 isWindow = false;
178 deleteLaterCalled = false;
179 isQuickItem = false;
180 willBeWidget = false;
181 wasWidget = false;
182}
183
184QObjectPrivate::~QObjectPrivate()
185{
186 auto thisThreadData = threadData.loadRelaxed();
187 if (extraData && !extraData->runningTimers.isEmpty()) {
188 if (Q_LIKELY(thisThreadData->thread.loadAcquire() == QThread::currentThread())) {
189 // unregister pending timers
190 if (thisThreadData->hasEventDispatcher())
191 thisThreadData->eventDispatcher.loadRelaxed()->unregisterTimers(object: q_ptr);
192
193 // release the timer ids back to the pool
194 for (int i = 0; i < extraData->runningTimers.size(); ++i)
195 QAbstractEventDispatcherPrivate::releaseTimerId(id: extraData->runningTimers.at(i));
196 } else {
197 qWarning(msg: "QObject::~QObject: Timers cannot be stopped from another thread");
198 }
199 }
200
201 if (postedEvents)
202 QCoreApplication::removePostedEvents(receiver: q_ptr, eventType: 0);
203
204 thisThreadData->deref();
205
206 if (metaObject)
207 metaObject->objectDestroyed(q_ptr);
208
209 delete extraData;
210}

212/*!
213 \internal
214 For a given metaobject, compute the signal offset, and the method offset (including signals)
215*/
216static void computeOffsets(const QMetaObject *metaobject, int *signalOffset, int *methodOffset)
217{
218 *signalOffset = *methodOffset = 0;
219 const QMetaObject *m = metaobject->d.superdata;
220 while (m) {
221 const QMetaObjectPrivate *d = QMetaObjectPrivate::get(metaobject: m);
222 *methodOffset += d->methodCount;
223 Q_ASSERT(d->revision >= 4);
224 *signalOffset += d->signalCount;
225 m = m->d.superdata;
226 }
227}

229// Used by QAccessibleWidget
230bool QObjectPrivate::isSender(const QObject *receiver, const char *signal) const
231{
232 Q_Q(const QObject);
233 int signal_index = signalIndex(signalName: signal);
234 ConnectionData *cd = connections.loadRelaxed();
235 if (signal_index < 0 || !cd)
236 return false;
237 QBasicMutexLocker locker(signalSlotLock(o: q));
238 if (signal_index < cd->signalVectorCount()) {
239 const QObjectPrivate::Connection *c = cd->signalVector.loadRelaxed()->at(i: signal_index).first.loadRelaxed();
240
241 while (c) {
242 if (c->receiver.loadRelaxed() == receiver)
243 return true;
244 c = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
245 }
246 }
247 return false;
248}
249
250// Used by QAccessibleWidget
251QObjectList QObjectPrivate::receiverList(const char *signal) const
252{
253 QObjectList returnValue;
254 int signal_index = signalIndex(signalName: signal);
255 ConnectionData *cd = connections.loadRelaxed();
256 if (signal_index < 0 || !cd)
257 return returnValue;
258 if (signal_index < cd->signalVectorCount()) {
259 const QObjectPrivate::Connection *c = cd->signalVector.loadRelaxed()->at(i: signal_index).first.loadRelaxed();
260
261 while (c) {
262 QObject *r = c->receiver.loadRelaxed();
263 if (r)
264 returnValue << r;
265 c = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
266 }
267 }
268 return returnValue;
269}
270
271// Used by QAccessibleWidget
272QObjectList QObjectPrivate::senderList() const
273{
274 QObjectList returnValue;
275 ConnectionData *cd = connections.loadRelaxed();
276 if (cd) {
277 QBasicMutexLocker locker(signalSlotLock(o: q_func()));
278 for (Connection *c = cd->senders; c; c = c->next)
279 returnValue << c->sender;
280 }
281 return returnValue;
282}

284inline void QObjectPrivate::ensureConnectionData()
285{
286 if (connections.loadRelaxed())
287 return;
288 ConnectionData *cd = new ConnectionData;
289 cd->ref.ref();
290 connections.storeRelaxed(newValue: cd);
291}

293/*!
294 \internal
295 Add the connection \a c to the list of connections of the sender's object
296 for the specified \a signal
297
298 The signalSlotLock() of the sender and receiver must be locked while calling
299 this function
300
301 Will also add the connection in the sender's list of the receiver.
302 */
303inline void QObjectPrivate::addConnection(int signal, Connection *c)
304{
305 Q_ASSERT(c->sender == q_ptr);
306 ensureConnectionData();
307 ConnectionData *cd = connections.loadRelaxed();
308 cd->resizeSignalVector(size: signal + 1);
309
310 ConnectionList &connectionList = cd->connectionsForSignal(signal);
311 if (connectionList.last.loadRelaxed()) {
312 Q_ASSERT(connectionList.last.loadRelaxed()->receiver.loadRelaxed());
313 connectionList.last.loadRelaxed()->nextConnectionList.storeRelaxed(newValue: c);
314 } else {
315 connectionList.first.storeRelaxed(newValue: c);
316 }
317 c->id = ++cd->currentConnectionId;
318 c->prevConnectionList = connectionList.last.loadRelaxed();
319 connectionList.last.storeRelaxed(newValue: c);
320
321 QObjectPrivate *rd = QObjectPrivate::get(o: c->receiver.loadRelaxed());
322 rd->ensureConnectionData();
323
324 c->prev = &(rd->connections.loadRelaxed()->senders);
325 c->next = *c->prev;
326 *c->prev = c;
327 if (c->next)
328 c->next->prev = &c->next;
329}

331void QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData::removeConnection(QObjectPrivate::Connection *c)
332{
333 Q_ASSERT(c->receiver.loadRelaxed());
334 ConnectionList &connections = signalVector.loadRelaxed()->at(i: c->signal_index);
335 c->receiver.storeRelaxed(newValue: nullptr);
336 QThreadData *td = c->receiverThreadData.loadRelaxed();
337 if (td)
338 td->deref();
339 c->receiverThreadData.storeRelaxed(newValue: nullptr);
340
341#ifndef QT_NO_DEBUG
342 bool found = false;
343 for (Connection *cc = connections.first.loadRelaxed(); cc; cc = cc->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed()) {
344 if (cc == c) {
345 found = true;
346 break;
347 }
348 }
349 Q_ASSERT(found);
350#endif
351
352 // remove from the senders linked list
353 *c->prev = c->next;
354 if (c->next)
355 c->next->prev = c->prev;
356 c->prev = nullptr;
357
358 if (connections.first.loadRelaxed() == c)
359 connections.first.storeRelaxed(newValue: c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed());
360 if (connections.last.loadRelaxed() == c)
361 connections.last.storeRelaxed(newValue: c->prevConnectionList);
362 Q_ASSERT(signalVector.loadRelaxed()->at(c->signal_index).first.loadRelaxed() != c);
363 Q_ASSERT(signalVector.loadRelaxed()->at(c->signal_index).last.loadRelaxed() != c);
364
365 // keep c->nextConnectionList intact, as it might still get accessed by activate
366 Connection *n = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
367 if (n)
368 n->prevConnectionList = c->prevConnectionList;
369 if (c->prevConnectionList)
370 c->prevConnectionList->nextConnectionList.storeRelaxed(newValue: n);
371 c->prevConnectionList = nullptr;
372
373 Q_ASSERT(c != orphaned.loadRelaxed());
374 // add c to orphanedConnections
375 Connection *o = nullptr;
376 /* No ABA issue here: When adding a node, we only care about the list head, it doesn't
377 * matter if the tail changes.
378 */
379 do {
380 o = orphaned.loadRelaxed();
381 c->nextInOrphanList = o;
382 } while (!orphaned.testAndSetRelease(expectedValue: o, newValue: c));
383
384#ifndef QT_NO_DEBUG
385 found = false;
386 for (Connection *cc = connections.first.loadRelaxed(); cc; cc = cc->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed()) {
387 if (cc == c) {
388 found = true;
389 break;
390 }
391 }
392 Q_ASSERT(!found);
393#endif
394
395}

397void QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData::cleanOrphanedConnectionsImpl(QObject *sender, LockPolicy lockPolicy)
398{
399 QBasicMutex *senderMutex = signalSlotLock(o: sender);
400 ConnectionOrSignalVector *c = nullptr;
401 {
402 std::unique_lock<QBasicMutex> lock(*senderMutex, std::defer_lock_t{});
403 if (lockPolicy == NeedToLock)
404 lock.lock();
405 if (ref.loadAcquire() > 1)
406 return;
407
408 // Since ref == 1, no activate() is in process since we locked the mutex. That implies,
409 // that nothing can reference the orphaned connection objects anymore and they can
410 // be safely deleted
411 c = orphaned.fetchAndStoreRelaxed(newValue: nullptr);
412 }
413 if (c) {
414 // Deleting c might run arbitrary user code, so we must not hold the lock
415 if (lockPolicy == AlreadyLockedAndTemporarilyReleasingLock) {
416 senderMutex->unlock();
417 deleteOrphaned(c);
418 senderMutex->lock();
419 } else {
420 deleteOrphaned(c);
421 }
422 }
423}
424
425inline void QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData::deleteOrphaned(QObjectPrivate::ConnectionOrSignalVector *o)
426{
427 while (o) {
428 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionOrSignalVector *next = nullptr;
429 if (SignalVector *v = ConnectionOrSignalVector::asSignalVector(c: o)) {
430 next = v->nextInOrphanList;
431 free(ptr: v);
432 } else {
433 QObjectPrivate::Connection *c = static_cast<Connection *>(o);
434 next = c->nextInOrphanList;
435 Q_ASSERT(!c->receiver.loadRelaxed());
436 Q_ASSERT(!c->prev);
437 c->freeSlotObject();
438 c->deref();
439 }
440 o = next;
441 }
442}

444/*! \internal
445
446 Returns \c true if the signal with index \a signal_index from object \a sender is connected.
447
448 \a signal_index must be the index returned by QObjectPrivate::signalIndex;
449*/
450bool QObjectPrivate::isSignalConnected(uint signalIndex, bool checkDeclarative) const
451{
452 if (checkDeclarative && isDeclarativeSignalConnected(signal_index: signalIndex))
453 return true;
454
455 ConnectionData *cd = connections.loadRelaxed();
456 if (!cd)
457 return false;
458 SignalVector *signalVector = cd->signalVector.loadRelaxed();
459 if (!signalVector)
460 return false;
461
462 if (signalVector->at(i: -1).first.loadRelaxed())
463 return true;
464
465 if (signalIndex < uint(cd->signalVectorCount())) {
466 const QObjectPrivate::Connection *c = signalVector->at(i: signalIndex).first.loadRelaxed();
467 while (c) {
468 if (c->receiver.loadRelaxed())
469 return true;
470 c = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
471 }
472 }
473 return false;
474}
475
476bool QObjectPrivate::maybeSignalConnected(uint signalIndex) const
477{
478 ConnectionData *cd = connections.loadRelaxed();
479 if (!cd)
480 return false;
481 SignalVector *signalVector = cd->signalVector.loadRelaxed();
482 if (!signalVector)
483 return false;
484
485 if (signalVector->at(i: -1).first.loadAcquire())
486 return true;
487
488 if (signalIndex < uint(cd->signalVectorCount())) {
489 const QObjectPrivate::Connection *c = signalVector->at(i: signalIndex).first.loadAcquire();
490 return c != nullptr;
491 }
492 return false;
493}

513/*!
514 \internal
515 */
516inline void QMetaCallEvent::allocArgs()
517{
518 if (!d.nargs_)
519 return;
520
521 constexpr size_t each = sizeof(void*) + sizeof(QMetaType);
522 void *const memory = d.nargs_ * each > sizeof(prealloc_) ?
523 calloc(nmemb: d.nargs_, size: each) : prealloc_;
524
525 Q_CHECK_PTR(memory);
526 d.args_ = static_cast<void **>(memory);
527}

597/*!
598 \internal
599 */
600QMetaCallEvent::~QMetaCallEvent()
601{
602 if (d.nargs_) {
603 QMetaType *t = types();
604 for (int i = 0; i < d.nargs_; ++i) {
605 if (t[i].isValid() && d.args_[i])
606 t[i].destroy(data: d.args_[i]);
607 }
608 if (reinterpret_cast<void *>(d.args_) != reinterpret_cast<void *>(prealloc_))
609 free(ptr: d.args_);
610 }
611 if (d.slotObj_)
612 d.slotObj_->destroyIfLastRef();
613}

615/*!
616 \internal
617 */
618void QMetaCallEvent::placeMetaCall(QObject *object)
619{
620 if (d.slotObj_) {
621 d.slotObj_->call(r: object, a: d.args_);
622 } else if (d.callFunction_ && d.method_offset_ <= object->metaObject()->methodOffset()) {
623 d.callFunction_(object, QMetaObject::InvokeMetaMethod, d.method_relative_, d.args_);
624 } else {
625 QMetaObject::metacall(object, QMetaObject::InvokeMetaMethod,
626 d.method_offset_ + d.method_relative_, d.args_);
627 }

630/*!
631 \class QSignalBlocker
632 \brief Exception-safe wrapper around QObject::blockSignals().
633 \since 5.3
634 \ingroup objectmodel
635 \inmodule QtCore
636
637 \reentrant
638
639 QSignalBlocker can be used wherever you would otherwise use a
640 pair of calls to blockSignals(). It blocks signals in its
641 constructor and in the destructor it resets the state to what
642 it was before the constructor ran.
643
644 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 53
645 is thus equivalent to
646 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 54
647
648 except the code using QSignalBlocker is safe in the face of
649 exceptions.
650
651 \sa QMutexLocker, QEventLoopLocker
652*/
653
654/*!
655 \fn QSignalBlocker::QSignalBlocker(QObject *object)
656
657 Constructor. Calls \a{object}->blockSignals(true).
658*/
659
660/*!
661 \fn QSignalBlocker::QSignalBlocker(QObject &object)
662 \overload
663
664 Calls \a{object}.blockSignals(true).
665*/
666
667/*!
668 \fn QSignalBlocker::QSignalBlocker(QSignalBlocker &&other)
669
670 Move-constructs a signal blocker from \a other. \a other will have
671 a no-op destructor, while responsibility for restoring the
672 QObject::signalsBlocked() state is transferred to the new object.
673*/
674
675/*!
676 \fn QSignalBlocker &QSignalBlocker::operator=(QSignalBlocker &&other)
677
678 Move-assigns this signal blocker from \a other. \a other will have
679 a no-op destructor, while responsibility for restoring the
680 QObject::signalsBlocked() state is transferred to this object.
681
682 The object's signals this signal blocker was blocking prior to
683 being moved to, if any, are unblocked \e except in the case where
684 both instances block the same object's signals and \c *this is
685 unblocked while \a other is not, at the time of the move.
686*/
687
688/*!
689 \fn QSignalBlocker::~QSignalBlocker()
690
691 Destructor. Restores the QObject::signalsBlocked() state to what it
692 was before the constructor ran, unless unblock() has been called
693 without a following reblock(), in which case it does nothing.
694*/
695
696/*!
697 \fn void QSignalBlocker::reblock()
698
699 Re-blocks signals after a previous unblock().
700
701 The numbers of reblock() and unblock() calls are not counted, so
702 every reblock() undoes any number of unblock() calls.
703*/
704
705/*!
706 \fn void QSignalBlocker::unblock()
707
708 Temporarily restores the QObject::signalsBlocked() state to what
709 it was before this QSignalBlocker's constructor ran. To undo, use
710 reblock().
711
712 The numbers of reblock() and unblock() calls are not counted, so
713 every unblock() undoes any number of reblock() calls.
714*/
715
716/*!
717 \class QObject
718 \inmodule QtCore
719 \brief The QObject class is the base class of all Qt objects.
720
721 \ingroup objectmodel
722
723 \reentrant
724
725 QObject is the heart of the Qt \l{Object Model}. The central
726 feature in this model is a very powerful mechanism for seamless
727 object communication called \l{signals and slots}. You can
728 connect a signal to a slot with connect() and destroy the
729 connection with disconnect(). To avoid never ending notification
730 loops you can temporarily block signals with blockSignals(). The
731 protected functions connectNotify() and disconnectNotify() make
732 it possible to track connections.
733
734 QObjects organize themselves in \l {Object Trees & Ownership}
735 {object trees}. When you create a QObject with another object as
736 parent, the object will automatically add itself to the parent's
737 children() list. The parent takes ownership of the object; i.e.,
738 it will automatically delete its children in its destructor. You
739 can look for an object by name and optionally type using
740 findChild() or findChildren().
741
742 Every object has an objectName() and its class name can be found
743 via the corresponding metaObject() (see QMetaObject::className()).
744 You can determine whether the object's class inherits another
745 class in the QObject inheritance hierarchy by using the
746 inherits() function.
747
748 When an object is deleted, it emits a destroyed() signal. You can
749 catch this signal to avoid dangling references to QObjects.
750
751 QObjects can receive events through event() and filter the events
752 of other objects. See installEventFilter() and eventFilter() for
753 details. A convenience handler, childEvent(), can be reimplemented
754 to catch child events.
755
756 Last but not least, QObject provides the basic timer support in
757 Qt; see QTimer for high-level support for timers.
758
759 Notice that the Q_OBJECT macro is mandatory for any object that
760 implements signals, slots or properties. You also need to run the
761 \l{moc}{Meta Object Compiler} on the source file. We strongly
762 recommend the use of this macro in all subclasses of QObject
763 regardless of whether or not they actually use signals, slots and
764 properties, since failure to do so may lead certain functions to
765 exhibit strange behavior.
766
767 All Qt widgets inherit QObject. The convenience function
768 isWidgetType() returns whether an object is actually a widget. It
769 is much faster than
770 \l{qobject_cast()}{qobject_cast}<QWidget *>(\e{obj}) or
771 \e{obj}->\l{inherits()}{inherits}("QWidget").
772
773 Some QObject functions, e.g. children(), return a QObjectList.
774 QObjectList is a typedef for QList<QObject *>.
775
776 \section1 Thread Affinity
777
778 A QObject instance is said to have a \e{thread affinity}, or that
779 it \e{lives} in a certain thread. When a QObject receives a
780 \l{Qt::QueuedConnection}{queued signal} or a \l{The Event
781 System#Sending Events}{posted event}, the slot or event handler
782 will run in the thread that the object lives in.
783
784 \note If a QObject has no thread affinity (that is, if thread()
785 returns zero), or if it lives in a thread that has no running event
786 loop, then it cannot receive queued signals or posted events.
787
788 By default, a QObject lives in the thread in which it is created.
789 An object's thread affinity can be queried using thread() and
790 changed using moveToThread().
791
792 All QObjects must live in the same thread as their parent. Consequently:
793
794 \list
795 \li setParent() will fail if the two QObjects involved live in
796 different threads.
797 \li When a QObject is moved to another thread, all its children
798 will be automatically moved too.
799 \li moveToThread() will fail if the QObject has a parent.
800 \li If QObjects are created within QThread::run(), they cannot
801 become children of the QThread object because the QThread does
802 not live in the thread that calls QThread::run().
803 \endlist
804
805 \note A QObject's member variables \e{do not} automatically become
806 its children. The parent-child relationship must be set by either
807 passing a pointer to the child's \l{QObject()}{constructor}, or by
808 calling setParent(). Without this step, the object's member variables
809 will remain in the old thread when moveToThread() is called.
810
811 \target No copy constructor
812 \section1 No Copy Constructor or Assignment Operator
813
814 QObject has neither a copy constructor nor an assignment operator.
815 This is by design. Actually, they are declared, but in a
816 \c{private} section with the macro Q_DISABLE_COPY(). In fact, all
817 Qt classes derived from QObject (direct or indirect) use this
818 macro to declare their copy constructor and assignment operator to
819 be private. The reasoning is found in the discussion on
820 \l{Identity vs Value} {Identity vs Value} on the Qt \l{Object
821 Model} page.
822
823 The main consequence is that you should use pointers to QObject
824 (or to your QObject subclass) where you might otherwise be tempted
825 to use your QObject subclass as a value. For example, without a
826 copy constructor, you can't use a subclass of QObject as the value
827 to be stored in one of the container classes. You must store
828 pointers.
829
830 \section1 Auto-Connection
831
832 Qt's meta-object system provides a mechanism to automatically connect
833 signals and slots between QObject subclasses and their children. As long
834 as objects are defined with suitable object names, and slots follow a
835 simple naming convention, this connection can be performed at run-time
836 by the QMetaObject::connectSlotsByName() function.
837
838 \l uic generates code that invokes this function to enable
839 auto-connection to be performed between widgets on forms created
840 with \e{Qt Designer}. More information about using auto-connection with \e{Qt Designer} is
841 given in the \l{Using a Designer UI File in Your Application} section of
842 the \e{Qt Designer} manual.
843
844 \section1 Dynamic Properties
845
846 From Qt 4.2, dynamic properties can be added to and removed from QObject
847 instances at run-time. Dynamic properties do not need to be declared at
848 compile-time, yet they provide the same advantages as static properties
849 and are manipulated using the same API - using property() to read them
850 and setProperty() to write them.
851
852 From Qt 4.3, dynamic properties are supported by
853 \l{Qt Designer's Widget Editing Mode#The Property Editor}{Qt Designer},
854 and both standard Qt widgets and user-created forms can be given dynamic
855 properties.
856
857 \section1 Internationalization (I18n)
858
859 All QObject subclasses support Qt's translation features, making it possible
860 to translate an application's user interface into different languages.
861
862 To make user-visible text translatable, it must be wrapped in calls to
863 the tr() function. This is explained in detail in the
864 \l{Writing Source Code for Translation} document.
865
866 \sa QMetaObject, QPointer, QObjectCleanupHandler, Q_DISABLE_COPY()
867 \sa {Object Trees & Ownership}
868*/
869

872 *****************************************************************************/

874// check the constructor's parent thread argument
875static bool check_parent_thread(QObject *parent,
876 QThreadData *parentThreadData,
877 QThreadData *currentThreadData)
878{
879 if (parent && parentThreadData != currentThreadData) {
880 QThread *parentThread = parentThreadData->thread.loadAcquire();
881 QThread *currentThread = currentThreadData->thread.loadAcquire();
882 qWarning(msg: "QObject: Cannot create children for a parent that is in a different thread.\n"
883 "(Parent is %s(%p), parent's thread is %s(%p), current thread is %s(%p)",
884 parent->metaObject()->className(),
885 parent,
886 parentThread ? parentThread->metaObject()->className() : "QThread",
887 parentThread,
888 currentThread ? currentThread->metaObject()->className() : "QThread",
889 currentThread);
890 return false;
891 }
892 return true;
893}

915/*!
916 \internal
917 */
918QObject::QObject(QObjectPrivate &dd, QObject *parent)
919 : d_ptr(&dd)
920{
921 Q_ASSERT_X(this != parent, Q_FUNC_INFO, "Cannot parent a QObject to itself");
922
923 Q_D(QObject);
924 d_ptr->q_ptr = this;
925 auto threadData = (parent && !parent->thread()) ? parent->d_func()->threadData.loadRelaxed() : QThreadData::current();
926 threadData->ref();
927 d->threadData.storeRelaxed(newValue: threadData);
928 if (parent) {
929 QT_TRY {
930 if (!check_parent_thread(parent, parentThreadData: parent ? parent->d_func()->threadData.loadRelaxed() : nullptr, currentThreadData: threadData))
931 parent = nullptr;
932 if (d->willBeWidget) {
933 if (parent) {
934 d->parent = parent;
935 d->parent->d_func()->children.append(t: this);
936 }
937 // no events sent here, this is done at the end of the QWidget constructor
938 } else {
939 setParent(parent);
940 }
941 } QT_CATCH(...) {
942 threadData->deref();
943 QT_RETHROW;
944 }
945 }
946 if (Q_UNLIKELY(qtHookData[QHooks::AddQObject]))
947 reinterpret_cast<QHooks::AddQObjectCallback>(qtHookData[QHooks::AddQObject])(this);
948 Q_TRACE(QObject_ctor, this);
949}

956/*!
957 Destroys the object, deleting all its child objects.
958
959 All signals to and from the object are automatically disconnected, and
960 any pending posted events for the object are removed from the event
961 queue. However, it is often safer to use deleteLater() rather than
962 deleting a QObject subclass directly.
963
964 \warning All child objects are deleted. If any of these objects
965 are on the stack or global, sooner or later your program will
966 crash. We do not recommend holding pointers to child objects from
967 outside the parent. If you still do, the destroyed() signal gives
968 you an opportunity to detect when an object is destroyed.
969
970 \warning Deleting a QObject while pending events are waiting to
971 be delivered can cause a crash. You must not delete the QObject
972 directly if it exists in a different thread than the one currently
973 executing. Use deleteLater() instead, which will cause the event
974 loop to delete the object after all pending events have been
975 delivered to it.
976
977 \sa deleteLater()
978*/
979
980QObject::~QObject()
981{
982 Q_D(QObject);
983 d->wasDeleted = true;
984 d->blockSig = 0; // unblock signals so we always emit destroyed()
985
986 if (!d->bindingStorage.isValid()) {
987 // this might be the case after an incomplete thread-move
988 // remove this object from the pending list in that case
989 if (QThread *ownThread = thread()) {
990 auto *privThread = static_cast<QThreadPrivate *>(
991 QObjectPrivate::get(o: ownThread));
992 privThread->removeObjectWithPendingBindingStatusChange(obj: this);
993 }
994 }
995
996 // If we reached this point, we need to clear the binding data
997 // as the corresponding properties are no longer useful
998 d->clearBindingStorage();
999
1000 QtSharedPointer::ExternalRefCountData *sharedRefcount = d->sharedRefcount.loadRelaxed();
1001 if (sharedRefcount) {
1002 if (sharedRefcount->strongref.loadRelaxed() > 0) {
1003 qWarning(msg: "QObject: shared QObject was deleted directly. The program is malformed and may crash.");
1004 // but continue deleting, it's too late to stop anyway
1005 }
1006
1007 // indicate to all QWeakPointers that this QObject has now been deleted
1008 sharedRefcount->strongref.storeRelaxed(newValue: 0);
1009 if (!sharedRefcount->weakref.deref())
1010 delete sharedRefcount;
1011 }
1012
1013 if (!d->wasWidget && d->isSignalConnected(signalIndex: 0)) {
1014 emit destroyed(this);
1015 }
1016
1017 if (!d->isDeletingChildren && d->declarativeData && QAbstractDeclarativeData::destroyed)
1018 QAbstractDeclarativeData::destroyed(d->declarativeData, this);
1019
1020 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData *cd = d->connections.loadRelaxed();
1021 if (cd) {
1022 if (cd->currentSender) {
1023 cd->currentSender->receiverDeleted();
1024 cd->currentSender = nullptr;
1025 }
1026
1027 QBasicMutex *signalSlotMutex = signalSlotLock(o: this);
1028 QBasicMutexLocker locker(signalSlotMutex);
1029
1030 // disconnect all receivers
1031 int receiverCount = cd->signalVectorCount();
1032 for (int signal = -1; signal < receiverCount; ++signal) {
1033 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionList &connectionList = cd->connectionsForSignal(signal);
1034
1035 while (QObjectPrivate::Connection *c = connectionList.first.loadRelaxed()) {
1036 Q_ASSERT(c->receiver.loadAcquire());
1037
1038 QBasicMutex *m = signalSlotLock(o: c->receiver.loadRelaxed());
1039 bool needToUnlock = QOrderedMutexLocker::relock(mtx1: signalSlotMutex, mtx2: m);
1040 if (c == connectionList.first.loadAcquire() && c->receiver.loadAcquire()) {
1041 cd->removeConnection(c);
1042 Q_ASSERT(connectionList.first.loadRelaxed() != c);
1043 }
1044 if (needToUnlock)
1045 m->unlock();
1046 }
1047 }
1048
1049 /* Disconnect all senders:
1050 */
1051 while (QObjectPrivate::Connection *node = cd->senders) {
1052 Q_ASSERT(node->receiver.loadAcquire());
1053 QObject *sender = node->sender;
1054 // Send disconnectNotify before removing the connection from sender's connection list.
1055 // This ensures any eventual destructor of sender will block on getting receiver's lock
1056 // and not finish until we release it.
1057 sender->disconnectNotify(signal: QMetaObjectPrivate::signal(m: sender->metaObject(), signal_index: node->signal_index));
1058 QBasicMutex *m = signalSlotLock(o: sender);
1059 bool needToUnlock = QOrderedMutexLocker::relock(mtx1: signalSlotMutex, mtx2: m);
1060 //the node has maybe been removed while the mutex was unlocked in relock?
1061 if (node != cd->senders) {
1062 // We hold the wrong mutex
1063 Q_ASSERT(needToUnlock);
1064 m->unlock();
1065 continue;
1066 }
1067
1068 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData *senderData = sender->d_func()->connections.loadRelaxed();
1069 Q_ASSERT(senderData);
1070
1071 QtPrivate::QSlotObjectBase *slotObj = nullptr;
1072 if (node->isSlotObject) {
1073 slotObj = node->slotObj;
1074 node->isSlotObject = false;
1075 }
1076
1077 senderData->removeConnection(c: node);
1078 /*
1079 When we unlock, another thread has the chance to delete/modify sender data.
1080 Thus we need to call cleanOrphanedConnections before unlocking. We use the
1081 variant of the function which assumes that the lock is already held to avoid
1082 a deadlock.
1083 We need to hold m, the sender lock. Considering that we might execute arbitrary user
1084 code, we should already release the signalSlotMutex here unless they are the same.
1085 */
1086 const bool locksAreTheSame = signalSlotMutex == m;
1087 if (!locksAreTheSame)
1088 locker.unlock();
1089 senderData->cleanOrphanedConnections(
1090 sender,
1091 lockPolicy: QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData::AlreadyLockedAndTemporarilyReleasingLock
1092 );
1093 if (needToUnlock)
1094 m->unlock();
1095
1096 if (locksAreTheSame) // otherwise already unlocked
1097 locker.unlock();
1098 if (slotObj)
1099 slotObj->destroyIfLastRef();
1100 locker.relock();
1101 }
1102
1103 // invalidate all connections on the object and make sure
1104 // activate() will skip them
1105 cd->currentConnectionId.storeRelaxed(newValue: 0);
1106 }
1107 if (cd && !cd->ref.deref())
1108 delete cd;
1109 d->connections.storeRelaxed(newValue: nullptr);
1110
1111 if (!d->children.isEmpty())
1112 d->deleteChildren();
1113
1114 if (Q_UNLIKELY(qtHookData[QHooks::RemoveQObject]))
1115 reinterpret_cast<QHooks::RemoveQObjectCallback>(qtHookData[QHooks::RemoveQObject])(this);
1116
1117 Q_TRACE(QObject_dtor, this);
1118
1119 if (d->parent) // remove it from parent object
1120 d->setParent_helper(nullptr);
1121}

1123inline QObjectPrivate::Connection::~Connection()
1124{
1125 if (ownArgumentTypes) {
1126 const int *v = argumentTypes.loadRelaxed();
1127 if (v != &DIRECT_CONNECTION_ONLY)
1128 delete[] v;
1129 }
1130 if (isSlotObject)
1131 slotObj->destroyIfLastRef();
1132}

1346/*!
1347 This virtual function receives events to an object and should
1348 return true if the event \a e was recognized and processed.
1349
1350 The event() function can be reimplemented to customize the
1351 behavior of an object.
1352
1353 Make sure you call the parent event class implementation
1354 for all the events you did not handle.
1355
1356 Example:
1357
1358 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 52
1359
1360 \sa installEventFilter(), timerEvent(), QCoreApplication::sendEvent(),
1361 QCoreApplication::postEvent()
1362*/
1363
1364bool QObject::event(QEvent *e)
1365{
1366 switch (e->type()) {
1367 case QEvent::Timer:
1368 timerEvent(event: (QTimerEvent *)e);
1369 break;
1370
1371 case QEvent::ChildAdded:
1372 case QEvent::ChildPolished:
1373 case QEvent::ChildRemoved:
1374 childEvent(event: (QChildEvent *)e);
1375 break;
1376
1377 case QEvent::DeferredDelete:
1378 qDeleteInEventHandler(o: this);
1379 break;
1380
1381 case QEvent::MetaCall:
1382 {
1383 QAbstractMetaCallEvent *mce = static_cast<QAbstractMetaCallEvent*>(e);
1384
1385 if (!d_func()->connections.loadRelaxed()) {
1386 QBasicMutexLocker locker(signalSlotLock(o: this));
1387 d_func()->ensureConnectionData();
1388 }
1389 QObjectPrivate::Sender sender(this, const_cast<QObject*>(mce->sender()), mce->signalId());
1390
1391 mce->placeMetaCall(object: this);
1392 break;
1393 }
1394
1395 case QEvent::ThreadChange: {
1396 Q_D(QObject);
1397 QThreadData *threadData = d->threadData.loadRelaxed();
1398 QAbstractEventDispatcher *eventDispatcher = threadData->eventDispatcher.loadRelaxed();
1399 if (eventDispatcher) {
1400 QList<QAbstractEventDispatcher::TimerInfo> timers = eventDispatcher->registeredTimers(object: this);
1401 if (!timers.isEmpty()) {
1402 // do not to release our timer ids back to the pool (since the timer ids are moving to a new thread).
1403 eventDispatcher->unregisterTimers(object: this);
1404 QMetaObject::invokeMethod(obj: this, member: "_q_reregisterTimers", c: Qt::QueuedConnection,
1405 Q_ARG(void*, (new QList<QAbstractEventDispatcher::TimerInfo>(timers))));
1406 }
1407 }
1408 break;
1409 }
1410
1411 default:
1412 if (e->type() >= QEvent::User) {
1413 customEvent(event: e);
1414 break;
1415 }
1416 return false;
1417 }
1418 return true;
1419}

1558 Returns the thread in which the object lives.

1562QThread *QObject::thread() const
1563{
1564 return d_func()->threadData.loadRelaxed()->thread.loadAcquire();
1565}
1566
1567/*!
1568 Changes the thread affinity for this object and its children. The
1569 object cannot be moved if it has a parent. Event processing will
1570 continue in the \a targetThread.
1571
1572 To move an object to the main thread, use QApplication::instance()
1573 to retrieve a pointer to the current application, and then use
1574 QApplication::thread() to retrieve the thread in which the
1575 application lives. For example:
1576
1577 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 7
1578
1579 If \a targetThread is \nullptr, all event processing for this object
1580 and its children stops, as they are no longer associated with any
1581 thread.
1582
1583 Note that all active timers for the object will be reset. The
1584 timers are first stopped in the current thread and restarted (with
1585 the same interval) in the \a targetThread. As a result, constantly
1586 moving an object between threads can postpone timer events
1587 indefinitely.
1588
1589 A QEvent::ThreadChange event is sent to this object just before
1590 the thread affinity is changed. You can handle this event to
1591 perform any special processing. Note that any new events that are
1592 posted to this object will be handled in the \a targetThread,
1593 provided it is not \nullptr: when it is \nullptr, no event processing
1594 for this object or its children can happen, as they are no longer
1595 associated with any thread.
1596
1597 \warning This function is \e not thread-safe; the current thread
1598 must be same as the current thread affinity. In other words, this
1599 function can only "push" an object from the current thread to
1600 another thread, it cannot "pull" an object from any arbitrary
1601 thread to the current thread. There is one exception to this rule
1602 however: objects with no thread affinity can be "pulled" to the
1603 current thread.
1604
1605 \sa thread()
1606 */
1607void QObject::moveToThread(QThread *targetThread)
1608{
1609 Q_D(QObject);
1610
1611 if (d->threadData.loadRelaxed()->thread.loadAcquire() == targetThread) {
1612 // object is already in this thread
1613 return;
1614 }
1615
1616 if (d->parent != nullptr) {
1617 qWarning(msg: "QObject::moveToThread: Cannot move objects with a parent");
1618 return;
1619 }
1620 if (d->isWidget) {
1621 qWarning(msg: "QObject::moveToThread: Widgets cannot be moved to a new thread");
1622 return;
1623 }
1624 if (!d->bindingStorage.isEmpty()) {
1625 qWarning(msg: "QObject::moveToThread: Can not move objects that contain bindings or are used in bindings to a new thread.");
1626 return;
1627 }
1628
1629 QThreadData *currentData = QThreadData::current();
1630 QThreadData *targetData = targetThread ? QThreadData::get2(thread: targetThread) : nullptr;
1631 QThreadData *thisThreadData = d->threadData.loadAcquire();
1632 if (!thisThreadData->thread.loadRelaxed() && currentData == targetData) {
1633 // one exception to the rule: we allow moving objects with no thread affinity to the current thread
1634 currentData = thisThreadData;
1635 } else if (thisThreadData != currentData) {
1636 qWarning(msg: "QObject::moveToThread: Current thread (%p) is not the object's thread (%p).\n"
1637 "Cannot move to target thread (%p)\n",
1638 currentData->thread.loadRelaxed(), thisThreadData->thread.loadRelaxed(), targetData ? targetData->thread.loadRelaxed() : nullptr);
1639
1640#ifdef Q_OS_MAC
1641 qWarning("You might be loading two sets of Qt binaries into the same process. "
1642 "Check that all plugins are compiled against the right Qt binaries. Export "
1643 "DYLD_PRINT_LIBRARIES=1 and check that only one set of binaries are being loaded.");
1644#endif
1645
1646 return;
1647 }
1648
1649 // prepare to move
1650 d->moveToThread_helper();
1651
1652 if (!targetData)
1653 targetData = new QThreadData(0);
1654
1655 // make sure nobody adds/removes connections to this object while we're moving it
1656 QMutexLocker l(signalSlotLock(o: this));
1657
1658 QOrderedMutexLocker locker(&currentData->postEventList.mutex,
1659 &targetData->postEventList.mutex);
1660
1661 // keep currentData alive (since we've got it locked)
1662 currentData->ref();
1663
1664 // move the object
1665 auto threadPrivate = targetThread
1666 ? static_cast<QThreadPrivate *>(QThreadPrivate::get(o: targetThread))
1667 : nullptr;
1668 QBindingStatus *bindingStatus = threadPrivate
1669 ? threadPrivate->bindingStatus()
1670 : nullptr;
1671 if (threadPrivate && !bindingStatus) {
1672 bindingStatus = threadPrivate->addObjectWithPendingBindingStatusChange(obj: this);
1673 }
1674 d_func()->setThreadData_helper(currentData, targetData, status: bindingStatus);
1675
1676 locker.unlock();
1677
1678 // now currentData can commit suicide if it wants to
1679 currentData->deref();
1680}
1681
1682void QObjectPrivate::moveToThread_helper()
1683{
1684 Q_Q(QObject);
1685 QEvent e(QEvent::ThreadChange);
1686 QCoreApplication::sendEvent(receiver: q, event: &e);
1687 bindingStorage.clear();
1688 for (int i = 0; i < children.size(); ++i) {
1689 QObject *child = children.at(i);
1690 child->d_func()->moveToThread_helper();
1691 }
1692}
1693
1694void QObjectPrivate::setThreadData_helper(QThreadData *currentData, QThreadData *targetData, QBindingStatus *status)
1695{
1696 Q_Q(QObject);
1697
1698 if (status) {
1699 // the new thread is already running
1700 this->bindingStorage.bindingStatus = status;
1701 }
1702
1703 // move posted events
1704 int eventsMoved = 0;
1705 for (int i = 0; i < currentData->postEventList.size(); ++i) {
1706 const QPostEvent &pe = currentData->postEventList.at(i);
1707 if (!pe.event)
1708 continue;
1709 if (pe.receiver == q) {
1710 // move this post event to the targetList
1711 targetData->postEventList.addEvent(ev: pe);
1712 const_cast<QPostEvent &>(pe).event = nullptr;
1713 ++eventsMoved;
1714 }
1715 }
1716 if (eventsMoved > 0 && targetData->hasEventDispatcher()) {
1717 targetData->canWait = false;
1718 targetData->eventDispatcher.loadRelaxed()->wakeUp();
1719 }
1720
1721 // the current emitting thread shouldn't restore currentSender after calling moveToThread()
1722 ConnectionData *cd = connections.loadRelaxed();
1723 if (cd) {
1724 if (cd->currentSender) {
1725 cd->currentSender->receiverDeleted();
1726 cd->currentSender = nullptr;
1727 }
1728
1729 // adjust the receiverThreadId values in the Connections
1730 if (cd) {
1731 auto *c = cd->senders;
1732 while (c) {
1733 QObject *r = c->receiver.loadRelaxed();
1734 if (r) {
1735 Q_ASSERT(r == q);
1736 targetData->ref();
1737 QThreadData *old = c->receiverThreadData.loadRelaxed();
1738 if (old)
1739 old->deref();
1740 c->receiverThreadData.storeRelaxed(newValue: targetData);
1741 }
1742 c = c->next;
1743 }
1744 }
1745
1746 }
1747
1748 // set new thread data
1749 targetData->ref();
1750 threadData.loadRelaxed()->deref();
1751
1752 // synchronizes with loadAcquire e.g. in QCoreApplication::postEvent
1753 threadData.storeRelease(newValue: targetData);
1754
1755 for (int i = 0; i < children.size(); ++i) {
1756 QObject *child = children.at(i);
1757 child->d_func()->setThreadData_helper(currentData, targetData, status);
1758 }
1759}
1760
1761void QObjectPrivate::_q_reregisterTimers(void *pointer)
1762{
1763 Q_Q(QObject);
1764 QList<QAbstractEventDispatcher::TimerInfo> *timerList = reinterpret_cast<QList<QAbstractEventDispatcher::TimerInfo> *>(pointer);
1765 QAbstractEventDispatcher *eventDispatcher = threadData.loadRelaxed()->eventDispatcher.loadRelaxed();
1766 for (int i = 0; i < timerList->size(); ++i) {
1767 const QAbstractEventDispatcher::TimerInfo &ti = timerList->at(i);
1768 eventDispatcher->registerTimer(timerId: ti.timerId, interval: ti.interval, timerType: ti.timerType, object: q);
1769 }
1770 delete timerList;
1771}

1774//
1775// The timer flag hasTimer is set when startTimer is called.
1776// It is not reset when killing the timer because more than
1777// one timer might be active.
1778//
1779
1780/*!
1781 Starts a timer and returns a timer identifier, or returns zero if
1782 it could not start a timer.
1783
1784 A timer event will occur every \a interval milliseconds until
1785 killTimer() is called. If \a interval is 0, then the timer event
1786 occurs once every time there are no more window system events to
1787 process.
1788
1789 The virtual timerEvent() function is called with the QTimerEvent
1790 event parameter class when a timer event occurs. Reimplement this
1791 function to get timer events.
1792
1793 If multiple timers are running, the QTimerEvent::timerId() can be
1794 used to find out which timer was activated.
1795
1796 Example:
1797
1798 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 8
1799
1800 Note that QTimer's accuracy depends on the underlying operating system and
1801 hardware. The \a timerType argument allows you to customize the accuracy of
1802 the timer. See Qt::TimerType for information on the different timer types.
1803 Most platforms support an accuracy of 20 milliseconds; some provide more.
1804 If Qt is unable to deliver the requested number of timer events, it will
1805 silently discard some.
1806
1807 The QTimer class provides a high-level programming interface with
1808 single-shot timers and timer signals instead of events. There is
1809 also a QBasicTimer class that is more lightweight than QTimer and
1810 less clumsy than using timer IDs directly.
1811
1812 \sa timerEvent(), killTimer(), QTimer::singleShot()
1813*/
1814
1815int QObject::startTimer(int interval, Qt::TimerType timerType)
1816{
1817 Q_D(QObject);
1818
1819 if (Q_UNLIKELY(interval < 0)) {
1820 qWarning(msg: "QObject::startTimer: Timers cannot have negative intervals");
1821 return 0;
1822 }
1823
1824 auto thisThreadData = d->threadData.loadRelaxed();
1825 if (Q_UNLIKELY(!thisThreadData->hasEventDispatcher())) {
1826 qWarning(msg: "QObject::startTimer: Timers can only be used with threads started with QThread");
1827 return 0;
1828 }
1829 if (Q_UNLIKELY(thread() != QThread::currentThread())) {
1830 qWarning(msg: "QObject::startTimer: Timers cannot be started from another thread");
1831 return 0;
1832 }
1833 int timerId = thisThreadData->eventDispatcher.loadRelaxed()->registerTimer(interval, timerType, object: this);
1834 d->ensureExtraData();
1835 d->extraData->runningTimers.append(t: timerId);
1836 return timerId;
1837}

1878/*!
1879 Kills the timer with timer identifier, \a id.
1880
1881 The timer identifier is returned by startTimer() when a timer
1882 event is started.
1883
1884 \sa timerEvent(), startTimer()
1885*/
1886
1887void QObject::killTimer(int id)
1888{
1889 Q_D(QObject);
1890 if (Q_UNLIKELY(thread() != QThread::currentThread())) {
1891 qWarning(msg: "QObject::killTimer: Timers cannot be stopped from another thread");
1892 return;
1893 }
1894 if (id) {
1895 int at = d->extraData ? d->extraData->runningTimers.indexOf(t: id) : -1;
1896 if (at == -1) {
1897 // timer isn't owned by this object
1898 qWarning(msg: "QObject::killTimer(): Error: timer id %d is not valid for object %p (%s, %ls), timer has not been killed",
1899 id,
1900 this,
1901 metaObject()->className(),
1902 qUtf16Printable(objectName()));
1903 return;
1904 }
1905
1906 auto thisThreadData = d->threadData.loadRelaxed();
1907 if (thisThreadData->hasEventDispatcher())
1908 thisThreadData->eventDispatcher.loadRelaxed()->unregisterTimer(timerId: id);
1909
1910 d->extraData->runningTimers.remove(i: at);
1911 QAbstractEventDispatcherPrivate::releaseTimerId(id);
1912 }
1913}

2201 return;
2202

2700
2701 This helper function calculates signal and method index for the given
2702 member in the specified class.
2703
2704 \list
2705 \li If member.mobj is \nullptr then both signalIndex and methodIndex are set to -1.
2706
2707 \li If specified member is not a member of obj instance class (or one of
2708 its parent classes) then both signalIndex and methodIndex are set to -1.
2709 \endlist
2710

2712 are working with QMetaMethod.
2713
2714 \a signalIndex is set to the signal index of member. If the member
2715 specified is not signal this variable is set to -1.
2716
2717 \a methodIndex is set to the method index of the member. If the
2718 member is not a method of the object specified by the \a obj argument this
2719 variable is set to -1.
2720*/
2721void QMetaObjectPrivate::memberIndexes(const QObject *obj,
2722 const QMetaMethod &member,
2723 int *signalIndex, int *methodIndex)
2724{
2725 *signalIndex = -1;
2726 *methodIndex = -1;
2727 if (!obj || !member.mobj)
2728 return;
2729 const QMetaObject *m = obj->metaObject();
2730 // Check that member is member of obj class
2731 while (m != nullptr && m != member.mobj)
2732 m = m->d.superdata;
2733 if (!m)
2734 return;
2735 *signalIndex = *methodIndex = member.relativeMethodIndex();
2736
2737 int signalOffset;
2738 int methodOffset;
2739 computeOffsets(metaobject: m, signalOffset: &signalOffset, methodOffset: &methodOffset);
2740
2741 *methodIndex += methodOffset;
2742 if (member.methodType() == QMetaMethod::Signal) {
2743 *signalIndex = originalClone(obj: m, local_method_index: *signalIndex);
2744 *signalIndex += signalOffset;
2745 } else {
2746 *signalIndex = -1;
2747 }

2800 signal is emitted.

2803 a handle to a connection if it successfully

2815 (exact same signal to the exact same slot on the same objects),
2816 the connection will fail and connect will return an invalid QMetaObject::Connection.

2819 and functors; they only apply to connecting to member functions.

2825 of types that are known to Qt's meta-object system, because Qt

3402/*
3403 \internal
3404 convert a signal index from the method range to the signal range
3405 */
3406static int methodIndexToSignalIndex(const QMetaObject **base, int signal_index)
3407{
3408 if (signal_index < 0)
3409 return signal_index;
3410 const QMetaObject *metaObject = *base;
3411 while (metaObject && metaObject->methodOffset() > signal_index)
3412 metaObject = metaObject->superClass();
3413
3414 if (metaObject) {
3415 int signalOffset, methodOffset;
3416 computeOffsets(metaobject: metaObject, signalOffset: &signalOffset, methodOffset: &methodOffset);
3417 if (signal_index < metaObject->methodCount())
3418 signal_index = QMetaObjectPrivate::originalClone(obj: metaObject, local_method_index: signal_index - methodOffset) + signalOffset;
3419 else
3420 signal_index = signal_index - methodOffset + signalOffset;
3421 *base = metaObject;
3422 }
3423 return signal_index;
3424}

3446/*!
3447 \internal
3448 Same as the QMetaObject::connect, but \a signal_index must be the result of QObjectPrivate::signalIndex
3449
3450 method_index is relative to the rmeta metaobject, if rmeta is \nullptr, then it is absolute index
3451
3452 the QObjectPrivate::Connection* has a refcount of 2, so it must be passed to a QMetaObject::Connection
3453 */
3454QObjectPrivate::Connection *QMetaObjectPrivate::connect(const QObject *sender,
3455 int signal_index, const QMetaObject *smeta,
3456 const QObject *receiver, int method_index,
3457 const QMetaObject *rmeta, int type, int *types)
3458{
3459 QObject *s = const_cast<QObject *>(sender);
3460 QObject *r = const_cast<QObject *>(receiver);
3461
3462 int method_offset = rmeta ? rmeta->methodOffset() : 0;
3463 Q_ASSERT(!rmeta || QMetaObjectPrivate::get(rmeta)->revision >= 6);
3464 QObjectPrivate::StaticMetaCallFunction callFunction = rmeta ? rmeta->d.static_metacall : nullptr;
3465
3466 QOrderedMutexLocker locker(signalSlotLock(o: sender),
3467 signalSlotLock(o: receiver));
3468
3469 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData *scd = QObjectPrivate::get(o: s)->connections.loadRelaxed();
3470 if (type & Qt::UniqueConnection && scd) {
3471 if (scd->signalVectorCount() > signal_index) {
3472 const QObjectPrivate::Connection *c2 = scd->signalVector.loadRelaxed()->at(i: signal_index).first.loadRelaxed();
3473
3474 int method_index_absolute = method_index + method_offset;
3475
3476 while (c2) {
3477 if (!c2->isSlotObject && c2->receiver.loadRelaxed() == receiver && c2->method() == method_index_absolute)
3478 return nullptr;
3479 c2 = c2->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
3480 }
3481 }
3482 }
3483 type &= ~Qt::UniqueConnection;
3484
3485 const bool isSingleShot = type & Qt::SingleShotConnection;
3486 type &= ~Qt::SingleShotConnection;
3487
3488 Q_ASSERT(type >= 0);
3489 Q_ASSERT(type <= 3);
3490
3491 std::unique_ptr<QObjectPrivate::Connection> c{new QObjectPrivate::Connection};
3492 c->sender = s;
3493 c->signal_index = signal_index;
3494 c->receiver.storeRelaxed(newValue: r);
3495 QThreadData *td = r->d_func()->threadData.loadAcquire();
3496 td->ref();
3497 c->receiverThreadData.storeRelaxed(newValue: td);
3498 c->method_relative = method_index;
3499 c->method_offset = method_offset;
3500 c->connectionType = type;
3501 c->isSlotObject = false;
3502 c->argumentTypes.storeRelaxed(newValue: types);
3503 c->callFunction = callFunction;
3504 c->isSingleShot = isSingleShot;
3505
3506 QObjectPrivate::get(o: s)->addConnection(signal: signal_index, c: c.get());
3507
3508 locker.unlock();
3509 QMetaMethod smethod = QMetaObjectPrivate::signal(m: smeta, signal_index);
3510 if (smethod.isValid())
3511 s->connectNotify(signal: smethod);
3512
3513 return c.release();

3545/*!
3546 \internal
3547 Helper function to remove the connection from the senders list and set the receivers to \nullptr
3548 */
3549bool QMetaObjectPrivate::disconnectHelper(QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData *connections, int signalIndex,
3550 const QObject *receiver, int method_index, void **slot,
3551 QBasicMutex *senderMutex, DisconnectType disconnectType)
3552{
3553 bool success = false;
3554
3555 auto &connectionList = connections->connectionsForSignal(signal: signalIndex);
3556 auto *c = connectionList.first.loadRelaxed();
3557 while (c) {
3558 QObject *r = c->receiver.loadRelaxed();
3559 if (r && (receiver == nullptr || (r == receiver
3560 && (method_index < 0 || (!c->isSlotObject && c->method() == method_index))
3561 && (slot == nullptr || (c->isSlotObject && c->slotObj->compare(a: slot)))))) {
3562 bool needToUnlock = false;
3563 QBasicMutex *receiverMutex = nullptr;
3564 if (r) {
3565 receiverMutex = signalSlotLock(o: r);
3566 // need to relock this receiver and sender in the correct order
3567 needToUnlock = QOrderedMutexLocker::relock(mtx1: senderMutex, mtx2: receiverMutex);
3568 }
3569 if (c->receiver.loadRelaxed())
3570 connections->removeConnection(c);
3571
3572 if (needToUnlock)
3573 receiverMutex->unlock();
3574
3575 success = true;
3576
3577 if (disconnectType == DisconnectOne)
3578 return success;
3579 }
3580 c = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
3581 }
3582 return success;

3585/*!
3586 \internal
3587 Same as the QMetaObject::disconnect, but \a signal_index must be the result of QObjectPrivate::signalIndex
3588 */
3589bool QMetaObjectPrivate::disconnect(const QObject *sender,
3590 int signal_index, const QMetaObject *smeta,
3591 const QObject *receiver, int method_index, void **slot,
3592 DisconnectType disconnectType)
3593{
3594 if (!sender)
3595 return false;
3596
3597 QObject *s = const_cast<QObject *>(sender);
3598
3599 QBasicMutex *senderMutex = signalSlotLock(o: sender);
3600 QBasicMutexLocker locker(senderMutex);
3601
3602 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData *scd = QObjectPrivate::get(o: s)->connections.loadRelaxed();
3603 if (!scd)
3604 return false;
3605
3606 bool success = false;
3607 {
3608 // prevent incoming connections changing the connections->receivers while unlocked
3609 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionDataPointer connections(scd);
3610
3611 if (signal_index < 0) {
3612 // remove from all connection lists
3613 for (int sig_index = -1; sig_index < scd->signalVectorCount(); ++sig_index) {
3614 if (disconnectHelper(connections: connections.data(), signalIndex: sig_index, receiver, method_index, slot, senderMutex, disconnectType))
3615 success = true;
3616 }
3617 } else if (signal_index < scd->signalVectorCount()) {
3618 if (disconnectHelper(connections: connections.data(), signalIndex: signal_index, receiver, method_index, slot, senderMutex, disconnectType))
3619 success = true;
3620 }
3621 }
3622
3623 locker.unlock();
3624 if (success) {
3625 scd->cleanOrphanedConnections(sender: s);
3626
3627 QMetaMethod smethod = QMetaObjectPrivate::signal(m: smeta, signal_index);
3628 if (smethod.isValid())
3629 s->disconnectNotify(signal: smethod);
3630 }
3631
3632 return success;
3633}

3649 if (hasParameters)

3666/*!
3667 \fn void QMetaObject::connectSlotsByName(QObject *object)
3668
3669 Searches recursively for all child objects of the given \a object, and connects
3670 matching signals from them to slots of \a object that follow the following form:
3671
3672 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 33
3673
3674 Let's assume our object has a child object of type \c{QPushButton} with
3675 the \l{QObject::objectName}{object name} \c{button1}. The slot to catch the
3676 button's \c{clicked()} signal would be:
3677
3678 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 34
3679
3680 If \a object itself has a properly set object name, its own signals are also
3681 connected to its respective slots.
3682
3683 \sa QObject::setObjectName()
3684 */
3685void QMetaObject::connectSlotsByName(QObject *o)
3686{
3687 if (!o)
3688 return;
3689 const QMetaObject *mo = o->metaObject();
3690 Q_ASSERT(mo);
3691 const QObjectList list = // list of all objects to look for matching signals including...
3692 o->findChildren<QObject *>() // all children of 'o'...
3693 << o; // and the object 'o' itself
3694
3695 // for each method/slot of o ...
3696 for (int i = 0; i < mo->methodCount(); ++i) {
3697 const QByteArray slotSignature = mo->method(index: i).methodSignature();
3698 const char *slot = slotSignature.constData();
3699 Q_ASSERT(slot);
3700
3701 // ...that starts with "on_", ...
3702 if (slot[0] != 'o' || slot[1] != 'n' || slot[2] != '_')
3703 continue;
3704
3705 // ...we check each object in our list, ...
3706 bool foundIt = false;
3707 for (int j = 0; j < list.size(); ++j) {
3708 const QObject *co = list.at(i: j);
3709 const QByteArray coName = co->objectName().toLatin1();
3710
3711 // ...discarding those whose objectName is not fitting the pattern "on_<objectName>_...", ...
3712 if (coName.isEmpty() || qstrncmp(str1: slot + 3, str2: coName.constData(), len: coName.size()) || slot[coName.size()+3] != '_')
3713 continue;
3714
3715 const char *signal = slot + coName.size() + 4; // the 'signal' part of the slot name
3716
3717 // ...for the presence of a matching signal "on_<objectName>_<signal>".
3718 const QMetaObject *smeta;
3719 int sigIndex = co->d_func()->signalIndex(signalName: signal, meta: &smeta);
3720 if (sigIndex < 0) {
3721 // if no exactly fitting signal (name + complete parameter type list) could be found
3722 // look for just any signal with the correct name and at least the slot's parameter list.
3723 // Note: if more than one of those signals exist, the one that gets connected is
3724 // chosen 'at random' (order of declaration in source file)
3725 QList<QByteArray> compatibleSignals;
3726 const QMetaObject *smo = co->metaObject();
3727 int sigLen = int(qstrlen(str: signal)) - 1; // ignore the trailing ')'
3728 for (int k = QMetaObjectPrivate::absoluteSignalCount(m: smo)-1; k >= 0; --k) {
3729 const QMetaMethod method = QMetaObjectPrivate::signal(m: smo, signal_index: k);
3730 if (!qstrncmp(str1: method.methodSignature().constData(), str2: signal, len: sigLen)) {
3731 smeta = method.enclosingMetaObject();
3732 sigIndex = k;
3733 compatibleSignals.prepend(t: method.methodSignature());
3734 }
3735 }
3736 if (compatibleSignals.size() > 1)
3737 qCWarning(lcConnectSlotsByName) << "QMetaObject::connectSlotsByName: Connecting slot" << slot
3738 << "with the first of the following compatible signals:" << compatibleSignals;
3739 }
3740
3741 if (sigIndex < 0)
3742 continue;
3743
3744 // we connect it...
3745 if (Connection(QMetaObjectPrivate::connect(sender: co, signal_index: sigIndex, smeta, receiver: o, method_index: i))) {
3746 foundIt = true;
3747 qCDebug(lcConnectSlotsByName, "%s",
3748 msgConnect(smeta, coName, QMetaObjectPrivate::signal(smeta, sigIndex), o, i).constData());
3749 // ...and stop looking for further objects with the same name.
3750 // Note: the Designer will make sure each object name is unique in the above
3751 // 'list' but other code may create two child objects with the same name. In
3752 // this case one is chosen 'at random'.
3753 break;
3754 }
3755 }
3756 if (foundIt) {
3757 // we found our slot, now skip all overloads
3758 while (mo->method(index: i + 1).attributes() & QMetaMethod::Cloned)
3759 ++i;
3760 } else if (!(mo->method(index: i).attributes() & QMetaMethod::Cloned)) {
3761 // check if the slot has the following signature: "on_..._...(..."
3762 int iParen = slotSignature.indexOf(c: '(');
3763 int iLastUnderscore = slotSignature.lastIndexOf(c: '_', from: iParen - 1);
3764 if (iLastUnderscore > 3)
3765 qCWarning(lcConnectSlotsByName,
3766 "QMetaObject::connectSlotsByName: No matching signal for %s", slot);
3767 }
3768 }
3769}

3802/*!
3803 \internal
3804
3805 \a signal must be in the signal index range (see QObjectPrivate::signalIndex()).
3806*/
3807static void queued_activate(QObject *sender, int signal, QObjectPrivate::Connection *c, void **argv)
3808{
3809 const int *argumentTypes = c->argumentTypes.loadRelaxed();
3810 if (!argumentTypes) {
3811 QMetaMethod m = QMetaObjectPrivate::signal(m: sender->metaObject(), signal_index: signal);
3812 argumentTypes = queuedConnectionTypes(method: m);
3813 if (!argumentTypes) // cannot queue arguments
3814 argumentTypes = &DIRECT_CONNECTION_ONLY;
3815 if (!c->argumentTypes.testAndSetOrdered(expectedValue: nullptr, newValue: argumentTypes)) {
3816 if (argumentTypes != &DIRECT_CONNECTION_ONLY)
3817 delete[] argumentTypes;
3818 argumentTypes = c->argumentTypes.loadRelaxed();
3819 }
3820 }
3821 if (argumentTypes == &DIRECT_CONNECTION_ONLY) // cannot activate
3822 return;
3823 int nargs = 1; // include return type
3824 while (argumentTypes[nargs - 1])
3825 ++nargs;
3826
3827 QBasicMutexLocker locker(signalSlotLock(o: c->receiver.loadRelaxed()));
3828 QObject *receiver = c->receiver.loadRelaxed();
3829 if (!receiver) {
3830 // the connection has been disconnected before we got the lock
3831 return;
3832 }
3833
3834 SlotObjectGuard slotObjectGuard { c->isSlotObject ? c->slotObj : nullptr };
3835 locker.unlock();
3836
3837 QMetaCallEvent *ev = c->isSlotObject ?
3838 new QMetaCallEvent(c->slotObj, sender, signal, nargs) :
3839 new QMetaCallEvent(c->method_offset, c->method_relative, c->callFunction, sender, signal, nargs);
3840
3841 void **args = ev->args();
3842 QMetaType *types = ev->types();
3843
3844 types[0] = QMetaType(); // return type
3845 args[0] = nullptr; // return value
3846
3847 if (nargs > 1) {
3848 for (int n = 1; n < nargs; ++n)
3849 types[n] = QMetaType(argumentTypes[n - 1]);
3850
3851 for (int n = 1; n < nargs; ++n)
3852 args[n] = types[n].create(copy: argv[n]);
3853 }
3854
3855 if (c->isSingleShot && !QObjectPrivate::removeConnection(c)) {
3856 delete ev;
3857 return;
3858 }
3859
3860 locker.relock();
3861 if (!c->isSingleShot && !c->receiver.loadRelaxed()) {
3862 // the connection has been disconnected while we were unlocked
3863 locker.unlock();
3864 delete ev;
3865 return;
3866 }
3867
3868 QCoreApplication::postEvent(receiver, event: ev);
3869}

3871template <bool callbacks_enabled>
3872void doActivate(QObject *sender, int signal_index, void **argv)
3873{
3874 QObjectPrivate *sp = QObjectPrivate::get(o: sender);
3875
3876 if (sp->blockSig)
3877 return;
3878
3879 Q_TRACE_SCOPE(QMetaObject_activate, sender, signal_index);
3880
3881 if (sp->isDeclarativeSignalConnected(signal_index)
3882 && QAbstractDeclarativeData::signalEmitted) {
3883 Q_TRACE_SCOPE(QMetaObject_activate_declarative_signal, sender, signal_index);
3884 QAbstractDeclarativeData::signalEmitted(sp->declarativeData, sender,
3885 signal_index, argv);
3886 }
3887
3888 const QSignalSpyCallbackSet *signal_spy_set = callbacks_enabled ? qt_signal_spy_callback_set.loadAcquire() : nullptr;
3889
3890 void *empty_argv[] = { nullptr };

3892 argv = empty_argv;
3893
3894 if (!sp->maybeSignalConnected(signalIndex: signal_index)) {
3895 // The possible declarative connection is done, and nothing else is connected
3896 if (callbacks_enabled && signal_spy_set->signal_begin_callback != nullptr)
3897 signal_spy_set->signal_begin_callback(sender, signal_index, argv);
3898 if (callbacks_enabled && signal_spy_set->signal_end_callback != nullptr)
3899 signal_spy_set->signal_end_callback(sender, signal_index);
3900 return;
3901 }
3902
3903 if (callbacks_enabled && signal_spy_set->signal_begin_callback != nullptr)
3904 signal_spy_set->signal_begin_callback(sender, signal_index, argv);
3905
3906 bool senderDeleted = false;
3907 {
3908 Q_ASSERT(sp->connections.loadAcquire());
3909 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionDataPointer connections(sp->connections.loadRelaxed());
3910 QObjectPrivate::SignalVector *signalVector = connections->signalVector.loadRelaxed();
3911
3912 const QObjectPrivate::ConnectionList *list;
3913 if (signal_index < signalVector->count())
3914 list = &signalVector->at(i: signal_index);
3915 else
3916 list = &signalVector->at(i: -1);
3917
3918 Qt::HANDLE currentThreadId = QThread::currentThreadId();
3919 bool inSenderThread = currentThreadId == QObjectPrivate::get(o: sender)->threadData.loadRelaxed()->threadId.loadRelaxed();
3920
3921 // We need to check against the highest connection id to ensure that signals added
3922 // during the signal emission are not emitted in this emission.
3923 uint highestConnectionId = connections->currentConnectionId.loadRelaxed();
3924 do {
3925 QObjectPrivate::Connection *c = list->first.loadRelaxed();
3926 if (!c)
3927 continue;
3928
3929 do {
3930 QObject * const receiver = c->receiver.loadRelaxed();
3931 if (!receiver)
3932 continue;
3933
3934 QThreadData *td = c->receiverThreadData.loadRelaxed();
3935 if (!td)
3936 continue;
3937

3939 if (inSenderThread) {
3940 receiverInSameThread = currentThreadId == td->threadId.loadRelaxed();
3941 } else {
3942 // need to lock before reading the threadId, because moveToThread() could interfere
3943 QMutexLocker lock(signalSlotLock(o: receiver));
3944 receiverInSameThread = currentThreadId == td->threadId.loadRelaxed();
3945 }
3946
3947
3948 // determine if this connection should be sent immediately or
3949 // put into the event queue
3950 if ((c->connectionType == Qt::AutoConnection && !receiverInSameThread)
3951 || (c->connectionType == Qt::QueuedConnection)) {
3952 queued_activate(sender, signal: signal_index, c, argv);
3953 continue;
3954#if QT_CONFIG(thread)
3955 } else if (c->connectionType == Qt::BlockingQueuedConnection) {
3956 if (receiverInSameThread) {
3957 qWarning(msg: "Qt: Dead lock detected while activating a BlockingQueuedConnection: "
3958 "Sender is %s(%p), receiver is %s(%p)",
3959 sender->metaObject()->className(), sender,
3960 receiver->metaObject()->className(), receiver);
3961 }
3962
3963 if (c->isSingleShot && !QObjectPrivate::removeConnection(c))
3964 continue;
3965
3966 QSemaphore semaphore;
3967 {
3968 QBasicMutexLocker locker(signalSlotLock(o: receiver));
3969 if (!c->isSingleShot && !c->receiver.loadAcquire())
3970 continue;
3971 QMetaCallEvent *ev = c->isSlotObject ?
3972 new QMetaCallEvent(c->slotObj, sender, signal_index, argv, &semaphore) :
3973 new QMetaCallEvent(c->method_offset, c->method_relative, c->callFunction,
3974 sender, signal_index, argv, &semaphore);
3975 QCoreApplication::postEvent(receiver, event: ev);
3976 }
3977 semaphore.acquire();
3978 continue;
3979#endif
3980 }
3981
3982 if (c->isSingleShot && !QObjectPrivate::removeConnection(c))
3983 continue;
3984
3985 QObjectPrivate::Sender senderData(receiverInSameThread ? receiver : nullptr, sender, signal_index);
3986
3987 if (c->isSlotObject) {
3988 SlotObjectGuard obj{c->slotObj};
3989
3990 {
3991 Q_TRACE_SCOPE(QMetaObject_activate_slot_functor, c->slotObj);
3992 obj->call(r: receiver, a: argv);
3993 }
3994 } else if (c->callFunction && c->method_offset <= receiver->metaObject()->methodOffset()) {
3995 //we compare the vtable to make sure we are not in the destructor of the object.
3996 const int method_relative = c->method_relative;
3997 const auto callFunction = c->callFunction;
3998 const int methodIndex = (Q_HAS_TRACEPOINTS || callbacks_enabled) ? c->method() : 0;
3999 if (callbacks_enabled && signal_spy_set->slot_begin_callback != nullptr)
4000 signal_spy_set->slot_begin_callback(receiver, methodIndex, argv);
4001
4002 {
4003 Q_TRACE_SCOPE(QMetaObject_activate_slot, receiver, methodIndex);
4004 callFunction(receiver, QMetaObject::InvokeMetaMethod, method_relative, argv);
4005 }
4006
4007 if (callbacks_enabled && signal_spy_set->slot_end_callback != nullptr)
4008 signal_spy_set->slot_end_callback(receiver, methodIndex);
4009 } else {
4010 const int method = c->method_relative + c->method_offset;
4011
4012 if (callbacks_enabled && signal_spy_set->slot_begin_callback != nullptr) {
4013 signal_spy_set->slot_begin_callback(receiver, method, argv);
4014 }
4015
4016 {
4017 Q_TRACE_SCOPE(QMetaObject_activate_slot, receiver, method);
4018 QMetaObject::metacall(receiver, QMetaObject::InvokeMetaMethod, method, argv);
4019 }
4020
4021 if (callbacks_enabled && signal_spy_set->slot_end_callback != nullptr)
4022 signal_spy_set->slot_end_callback(receiver, method);
4023 }
4024 } while ((c = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed()) != nullptr && c->id <= highestConnectionId);
4025
4026 } while (list != &signalVector->at(i: -1) &&
4027 //start over for all signals;
4028 ((list = &signalVector->at(i: -1)), true));
4029
4030 if (connections->currentConnectionId.loadRelaxed() == 0)
4031 senderDeleted = true;
4032 }
4033 if (!senderDeleted) {
4034 sp->connections.loadRelaxed()->cleanOrphanedConnections(sender);
4035
4036 if (callbacks_enabled && signal_spy_set->signal_end_callback != nullptr)
4037 signal_spy_set->signal_end_callback(sender, signal_index);
4038 }
4039}

4080/*!
4081 \internal
4082 Returns the signal index used in the internal connections->receivers vector.
4083
4084 It is different from QMetaObject::indexOfSignal(): indexOfSignal is the same as indexOfMethod
4085 while QObjectPrivate::signalIndex is smaller because it doesn't give index to slots.
4086
4087 If \a meta is not \nullptr, it is set to the meta-object where the signal was found.
4088*/
4089int QObjectPrivate::signalIndex(const char *signalName,
4090 const QMetaObject **meta) const
4091{
4092 Q_Q(const QObject);
4093 const QMetaObject *base = q->metaObject();
4094 Q_ASSERT(QMetaObjectPrivate::get(base)->revision >= 7);
4095 QArgumentTypeArray types;
4096 QByteArray name = QMetaObjectPrivate::decodeMethodSignature(signature: signalName, types);
4097 int relative_index = QMetaObjectPrivate::indexOfSignalRelative(
4098 baseObject: &base, name, argc: types.size(), types: types.constData());
4099 if (relative_index < 0)
4100 return relative_index;
4101 relative_index = QMetaObjectPrivate::originalClone(obj: base, local_method_index: relative_index);
4102 if (meta)
4103 *meta = base;
4104 return relative_index + QMetaObjectPrivate::signalOffset(m: base);
4105}

4111/*!
4112 Sets the value of the object's \a name property to \a value.
4113
4114 If the property is defined in the class using Q_PROPERTY then
4115 true is returned on success and false otherwise. If the property
4116 is not defined using Q_PROPERTY, and therefore not listed in the
4117 meta-object, it is added as a dynamic property and false is returned.
4118
4119 Information about all available properties is provided through the
4120 metaObject() and dynamicPropertyNames().
4121
4122 Dynamic properties can be queried again using property() and can be
4123 removed by setting the property value to an invalid QVariant.
4124 Changing the value of a dynamic property causes a QDynamicPropertyChangeEvent
4125 to be sent to the object.
4126
4127 \b{Note:} Dynamic properties starting with "_q_" are reserved for internal
4128 purposes.
4129
4130 \sa property(), metaObject(), dynamicPropertyNames(), QMetaProperty::write()
4131*/
4132bool QObject::setProperty(const char *name, const QVariant &value)
4133{
4134 Q_D(QObject);
4135 const QMetaObject *meta = metaObject();
4136 if (!name || !meta)
4137 return false;
4138
4139 int id = meta->indexOfProperty(name);
4140 if (id < 0) {
4141 d->ensureExtraData();
4142
4143 const int idx = d->extraData->propertyNames.indexOf(t: name);
4144
4145 if (!value.isValid()) {
4146 if (idx == -1)
4147 return false;
4148 d->extraData->propertyNames.removeAt(i: idx);
4149 d->extraData->propertyValues.removeAt(i: idx);
4150 } else {
4151 if (idx == -1) {
4152 d->extraData->propertyNames.append(t: name);
4153 d->extraData->propertyValues.append(t: value);
4154 } else {
4155 if (value.userType() == d->extraData->propertyValues.at(i: idx).userType()
4156 && value == d->extraData->propertyValues.at(i: idx))
4157 return false;
4158 d->extraData->propertyValues[idx] = value;
4159 }
4160 }
4161
4162 QDynamicPropertyChangeEvent ev(name);
4163 QCoreApplication::sendEvent(receiver: this, event: &ev);
4164
4165 return false;
4166 }
4167 QMetaProperty p = meta->property(index: id);
4168#ifndef QT_NO_DEBUG
4169 if (!p.isWritable())
4170 qWarning("%s::setProperty: Property \"%s\" invalid,"
4171 " read-only or does not exist", metaObject()->className(), name);
4172#endif
4173 return p.write(obj: this, value);
4174}

4176/*!
4177 Returns the value of the object's \a name property.
4178
4179 If no such property exists, the returned variant is invalid.
4180
4181 Information about all available properties is provided through the
4182 metaObject() and dynamicPropertyNames().
4183
4184 \sa setProperty(), QVariant::isValid(), metaObject(), dynamicPropertyNames()
4185*/
4186QVariant QObject::property(const char *name) const
4187{
4188 Q_D(const QObject);
4189 const QMetaObject *meta = metaObject();
4190 if (!name || !meta)
4191 return QVariant();
4192
4193 int id = meta->indexOfProperty(name);
4194 if (id < 0) {
4195 if (!d->extraData)
4196 return QVariant();
4197 const int i = d->extraData->propertyNames.indexOf(t: name);
4198 return d->extraData->propertyValues.value(i);
4199 }
4200 QMetaProperty p = meta->property(index: id);
4201#ifndef QT_NO_DEBUG
4202 if (!p.isReadable())
4203 qWarning("%s::property: Property \"%s\" invalid or does not exist",
4204 metaObject()->className(), name);
4205#endif
4206 return p.read(obj: this);
4207}

4258/*!
4259 Dumps information about signal connections, etc. for this object
4260 to the debug output.
4261
4262 \note Before Qt 5.9, this function was not const.
4263
4264 \sa dumpObjectTree()
4265*/
4266
4267void QObject::dumpObjectInfo() const
4268{
4269 qDebug(msg: "OBJECT %s::%s", metaObject()->className(),
4270 objectName().isEmpty() ? "unnamed" : objectName().toLocal8Bit().data());
4271
4272 Q_D(const QObject);
4273 QBasicMutexLocker locker(signalSlotLock(o: this));
4274
4275 // first, look for connections where this object is the sender
4276 qDebug(msg: " SIGNALS OUT");
4277
4278 QObjectPrivate::ConnectionData *cd = d->connections.loadRelaxed();
4279 if (cd && cd->signalVectorCount() > 0) {
4280 QObjectPrivate::SignalVector *signalVector = cd->signalVector.loadRelaxed();
4281 for (int signal_index = 0; signal_index < signalVector->count(); ++signal_index) {
4282 const QObjectPrivate::Connection *c = signalVector->at(i: signal_index).first.loadRelaxed();
4283 if (!c)
4284 continue;
4285 const QMetaMethod signal = QMetaObjectPrivate::signal(m: metaObject(), signal_index);
4286 qDebug(msg: " signal: %s", signal.methodSignature().constData());
4287
4288 // receivers
4289 while (c) {
4290 if (!c->receiver.loadRelaxed()) {
4291 qDebug(msg: " <Disconnected receiver>");
4292 c = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
4293 continue;
4294 }
4295 if (c->isSlotObject) {
4296 qDebug(msg: " <functor or function pointer>");
4297 c = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
4298 continue;
4299 }
4300 const QMetaObject *receiverMetaObject = c->receiver.loadRelaxed()->metaObject();
4301 const QMetaMethod method = receiverMetaObject->method(index: c->method());

4303 receiverMetaObject->className(),
4304 c->receiver.loadRelaxed()->objectName().isEmpty() ? "unnamed" : qPrintable(c->receiver.loadRelaxed()->objectName()),
4305 method.methodSignature().constData());
4306 c = c->nextConnectionList.loadRelaxed();
4307 }
4308 }
4309 } else {
4310 qDebug( msg: " <None>" );
4311 }
4312
4313 // now look for connections where this object is the receiver
4314 qDebug(msg: " SIGNALS IN");
4315
4316 if (cd && cd->senders) {
4317 for (QObjectPrivate::Connection *s = cd->senders; s; s = s->next) {
4318 QByteArray slotName = QByteArrayLiteral("<unknown>");
4319 if (!s->isSlotObject) {
4320 const QMetaMethod slot = metaObject()->method(index: s->method());
4321 slotName = slot.methodSignature();
4322 }
4323 qDebug(msg: " <-- %s::%s %s",
4324 s->sender->metaObject()->className(),
4325 s->sender->objectName().isEmpty() ? "unnamed" : qPrintable(s->sender->objectName()),
4326 slotName.constData());
4327 }
4328 } else {
4329 qDebug(msg: " <None>");
4330 }
4331}

4604/*!

4609 The Q_GADGET_EXPORT macro works exactly like the Q_GADGET macro.
4610 However, the \c{staticMetaObject} variable that is made available (see
4611 Q_GADGET) is declared with the supplied \a EXPORT_MACRO qualifier. This is
4612 useful if the object needs to be exported from a dynamic library, but the

4614 inline functions).

4867/*!
4868 \fn template<typename PointerToMemberFunction> QMetaObject::Connection QObject::connect(const QObject *sender, PointerToMemberFunction signal, const QObject *receiver, PointerToMemberFunction method, Qt::ConnectionType type)
4869 \overload connect()
4870 \threadsafe
4871
4872 Creates a connection of the given \a type from the \a signal in
4873 the \a sender object to the \a method in the \a receiver object.
4874 Returns a handle to the connection that can be used to disconnect
4875 it later.
4876
4877 The signal must be a function declared as a signal in the header.
4878 The slot function can be any member function that can be connected
4879 to the signal.
4880 A slot can be connected to a given signal if the signal has at
4881 least as many arguments as the slot, and there is an implicit
4882 conversion between the types of the corresponding arguments in the
4883 signal and the slot.
4884
4885 Example:
4886
4887 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 44
4888
4889 This example ensures that the label always displays the current
4890 line edit text.
4891
4892 A signal can be connected to many slots and signals. Many signals
4893 can be connected to one slot.
4894
4895 If a signal is connected to several slots, the slots are activated
4896 in the same order as the order the connection was made, when the
4897 signal is emitted
4898
4899 The function returns an handle to a connection if it successfully
4900 connects the signal to the slot. The Connection handle will be invalid
4901 if it cannot create the connection, for example, if QObject is unable
4902 to verify the existence of \a signal (if it was not declared as a signal)
4903 You can check if the QMetaObject::Connection is valid by casting it to a bool.
4904
4905 By default, a signal is emitted for every connection you make;
4906 two signals are emitted for duplicate connections. You can break
4907 all of these connections with a single disconnect() call.
4908 If you pass the Qt::UniqueConnection \a type, the connection will only
4909 be made if it is not a duplicate. If there is already a duplicate
4910 (exact same signal to the exact same slot on the same objects),
4911 the connection will fail and connect will return an invalid QMetaObject::Connection.
4912
4913 The optional \a type parameter describes the type of connection
4914 to establish. In particular, it determines whether a particular
4915 signal is delivered to a slot immediately or queued for delivery
4916 at a later time. If the signal is queued, the parameters must be
4917 of types that are known to Qt's meta-object system, because Qt
4918 needs to copy the arguments to store them in an event behind the
4919 scenes. If you try to use a queued connection and get the error
4920 message
4921
4922 \snippet code/src_corelib_kernel_qobject.cpp 25
4923
4924 make sure to declare the argument type with Q_DECLARE_METATYPE
4925
4926 Overloaded functions can be resolved with help of \l qOverload.
4927
4928 \sa {Differences between String-Based and Functor-Based Connections}
